         b'class="page-header">\n\t\t\t\t\t<h1 class="page-title">Category Ar'
         b'chives: <span>Goal Modelling</span></h1>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</hea'
         b'der>\n\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t<article id="post'
         b'-163" class="post-163 post type-post status-publish format-standard '
         b'hentry category-goal-modelling-2 category-research-impact">\n\t\t<h'
         b'eader class="entry-header">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<h1 class="entry-title"><a'
         b' href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/goal-modelling-for-dna-programming'
         b'/" title="Permalink to Goal Modelling for DNA Programming" rel="book'
         b'mark">Goal Modelling for DNA Programming</a></h1>\n\t\t\t\n\t\t'
         b'\t\t\t\t<div class="entry-meta">\n\t\t\t\t<span class="sep">Poste'
         b'd on </span><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/goal-modelling-for-d'
         b'na-programming/" title="8:49 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-d'
         b'ate" datetime="2012-06-04T20:49:55+00:00" pubdate>June 4, 2012</time'
         b'></a><span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span cl'
         b'ass="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac'
         b'.uk/author/ucaceyl/" title="View all posts by Emmanuel" rel="author"'
         b'>Emmanuel</a></span></span>\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-meta -->\n\t\t\t'
         b'\n\t\t\t\t\t</header><!-- .entry-header -->\n\n\t\t\t\t<div class="e'
         b'ntry-content">\n\t\t\t<p>Sometimes, your research can have influence'
         b's in unexpected places. A couple of months ago, Google Scholar alert'
         b'ed me of a <a title="Lutz et al., Engineering and Verifying Requirem'
         b'ents for Programmable Self-Assembling Nanomachines, ICSE 2012" href='
         b'"http://www.cs.iastate.edu/%7Erlutz/publications/icse12_accepted.pdf'
         b'">paper</a> by Robyn Lutz and colleagues at NASA JPL and the Iowa St'
         b'ate University that applies goal-oriented requirements modelling to '
         b'the design and analysis of programmable DNA nanotechnology. This is '
         b'part of the fascinating field of <a title="UCL synthetic biology gro'
         b'up" href="http://www.ucl.ac.uk/synbion">synthetic biology</a>; the i'
         b'dea that we could engineer new biological systems performing useful '
         b'functions that can\xe2\x80\x99t be performed by natural biologica'
         b'l systems, much in the same way that material engineers have develop'
         b'ed new materials such alloys or reinforced concrete that exhibit pro'
         b'perties that could not be found in natural metals and stones. These '
         b'biological systems are composed of huge numbers of nanoscale living '
         b'organisms that when put together have some global emergent propertie'
         b's and behaviours. The individual organisms are designed by programmi'
         b'ng their DNA, long sequences of A-T-C-G letters, which is the equiva'
         b'lent of machine language instructions for a computer program. In fac'
         b't, this period in the development of synthetic biology is often comp'
         b'ared to the early days of computer science, with plenty of stories a'
         b'nd scares about people hacking systems in their garage. That'
         b'\xe2\x80\x99s about how much I understand about it at the moment.'
         b'</p>\n<p>Interestingly, software engineering concepts appear to p'
         b'lay a significant role in the development of this field. This <a tit'
         b'le="Adventures in Synthetic Biology" href="http://openwetware.org/wi'
         b'ki/Adventures">comic</a> published in Nature, for example, refers to'
         b' concepts such as abstraction, information hiding, and interfaces th'
         b'at are at the heart of software architecture. The research appears t'
         b'o still be laying out the basic technological foundations and, apart'
         b' from important general concerns about safety and security, there do'
         b'esn\xe2\x80\x99t seem to be much explicit consideration for requi'
         b'rements and the relations between requirements and architectures for'
         b' such systems. As the technology progresses, this will certainly cha'
         b'nge. The paper by Robyn Lutz and her colleagues is probably the firs'
         b't to investigate what requirements engineering methods for such syst'
         b'ems might look like. The paper will be presented at the New Idea and'
         b' Emerging Research track at <a href="http://www.ifi.uzh.ch/icse2012/'
         b'">ICSE</a> this week. It is one of the many talks I\xe2\x80\x99m '
         b'looking forward to.</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-content -->\n\t'
         b'\t\n\t\t<footer class="entry-meta">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<spa'
         b'n class="cat-links">\n\t\t\t\t<span class="entry-utility-prep ent'
         b'ry-utility-prep-cat-links">Posted in</span> <a href="http://letier.c'
         b's.ucl.ac.uk/category/goal-modelling-2/" title="View all posts in Goa'
         b'l Modelling" rel="category tag">Goal Modelling</a>, <a href="http://'
         b'letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/category/research-impact/" title="View all posts'
         b' in Research Impact" rel="category tag">Research Impact</a>\t\t\t</'
         b'span>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t</footer><!-- #entry-me'
         b'ta -->\n\t</article><!-- #post-163 -->\n\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t<a'
         b'rticle id="post-668" class="post-668 post type-post status-publish f'
         b'ormat-standard hentry category-goal-modelling-2 category-requirement'
         b's-risks">\n\t\t<header class="entry-header">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<h1 clas'
         b's="entry-title"><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/incomplete-obsta'
         b'cle-resolution-in-patient-monitoring-system/" title="Permalink to In'
         b'complete Obstacle Resolution in Patient Monitoring System" rel="book'
         b'mark">Incomplete Obstacle Resolution in Patient Monitoring System</a'
         b'></h1>\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class="entry-meta">\n\t\t\t\t<span '
         b'class="sep">Posted on </span><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/inc'
         b'omplete-obstacle-resolution-in-patient-monitoring-system/" title="9:'
         b'39 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2012-05-31T'
         b'21:39:23+00:00" pubdate>May 31, 2012</time></a><span class="by-autho'
         b'r"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcard"><a clas'
         b's="url fn n" href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/author/ucaceyl/" title'
         b'="View all posts by Emmanuel" rel="author">Emmanuel</a></span></span'
         b'>\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-meta -->\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t</header><!-'
         b'- .entry-header -->\n\n\t\t\t\t<div class="entry-content">\n\t\t\t'
         b'<p>Patient monitoring is <a href="http://domino.watson.ibm.com/tchjr'
         b'/journalindex.nsf/0/751ad3c1867f587a85256bfa00685aaa?OpenDocument">o'
         b'ne of the oldest case studies</a> in software engineering and it has'
         b' been used extensively to illustrate a variety of modelling and anal'
         b'ysis techniques. Yet, incidents with patient monitoring systems stil'
         b'l happen and we can still learn by looking at them.</p>\n<p>This '
         b'story was reported on <a href="http://catless.ncl.ac.uk/Risks/26.86.'
         b'html#subj1">the RISK forum</a> this week.</p>\n<blockquote><p><st'
         b'rong>Patient Died at New York VA Hospital After Alarm Was Ignored</s'
         b'trong></p>\n<p>Charles Ornstein and Tracy Weber, ProPublica, 15 M'
         b'ay 2012</p>\n<p>Registered nurses at a Manhattan Veterans Affairs'
         b' hospital failed to notice a patient had become disconnected from a '
         b'cardiac monitor until after his heart had stopped and he could not b'
         b'e revived, according to a report Monday from the VA inspector genera'
         b'l.</p>\n<p>The incident from last June was the second such death '
         b'at the hospital involving a patient connected to a monitor in a six-'
         b'month period. The first, along with two earlier deaths at a Denver V'
         b'A hospital, raised questions about nursing competency in the VA syst'
         b'em, ProPublica reported last month.</p>\n<p>The deaths also promp'
         b'ted a broader review of skills and training of VA nurses. Only half '
         b'of 29 VA facilities surveyed by the inspector general in a recent re'
         b'port had adequately documented that their nurses had skills to perfo'
         b'rm their duties. Even though some nurses &#8220;did not demonstrate '
         b'competency in one or more required skills,&#8221; the government rep'
         b'ort stated, there was no evidence of retraining. &#8230;</p>\n<p>'
         b'<a href="http://www.propublica.org/article/patient-died-at-new-york-'
         b'va-hospital-after-alarm-was-ignored">http://www.propublica.org/artic'
         b'le/patient-died-at-new-york-va-hospital-after-alarm-was-ignored</a><'
         b'/p></blockquote>\n<p>So it seems to be the nurses&#8217; fault an'
         b'd the solution to prevent this from happening again is better nurse '
         b'training. But is this the only way to look at this problem? Blaming '
         b'the operator is a common reaction when this sort of incidents occur,'
         b' but very often the operator\xe2\x80\x99s error is caused or made'
         b' more likely by poor decisions in the system design.</p>\n<p>Bein'
         b'g curious, I\xe2\x80\x99ve had a quick look at the <a href="http:'
         b'//www.propublica.org/documents/item/356534-vaoig-nyc1.html">more det'
         b'ailed report</a> on these incidents, and this is how it describes th'
         b'e different kinds of\xc2\xa0 alarm in this system:</p>\n<blockquote'
         b'><p>The telemetry monitoring equipment at the system triggers three '
         b'types of audible alarms:</p></blockquote>\n<blockquote><p><strong'
         b'>- Red Alarm </strong>is an audible critical alarm that is loud and '
         b'continuous. It indicates the need to immediately check on a pati'
         b'ent\xe2\x80\x99s status and vital signs.<strong></strong></p></bl'
         b'ockquote>\n<blockquote><p><strong>- Y</strong><strong>ellow Alarm'
         b' </strong>is a quieter and intermittent audible alarm that stops aft'
         b'er several minutes. It indicates a temporary irregularity in the hea'
         b'rt rate or rhythm that is not immediately critical.<strong></strong>'
         b'</p></blockquote>\n<blockquote><p><strong>- Blue Alarm </strong>i'
         b's similar to the yellow alarm and indicates a problem with the syste'
         b'm itself or an improperly connected, or disconnected, telemetry lead'
         b'.</p></blockquote>\n<p>I\xe2\x80\x99m sure you all see what the pr'
         b'oblem might have been; having similar alarms for possibly critical a'
         b'nd non-critical events is probably not a good idea.</p>\n<p>This '
         b'incident provides a good example to illustrate the technique of<a hr'
         b'ef="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/e.letier/publications/TSE-Obstacle'
         b's.pdf"> goal-oriented obstacle analysis</a>.</p>\n<p>An obstacle '
         b'is something that could go wrong and prevent a system from satisfyin'
         b'g its goals. Here, the system designers had identified that the obst'
         b'acle &#8220;Patient is accidentally disconnected from the monitor&#8'
         b'221; would obstruct the goal &#8220;Maintain Accurate Measures of Pa'
         b'tient Vital Signs&#8221; which itself contribute, along many other g'
         b'oals, to the goal &#8220;Keep Patient Alive&#8221;. The resolution o'
         b'f that obstacle was to include an alarm to warn the nurses when this'
         b' happens (technically, in our framework we would call this an obstac'
         b'le mitigation).</p>\n<p>Unfortunately, they may not have paid eno'
         b'ugh attention to the goal that this obstacle resolution was meant to'
         b' achieve. The goal is not just to send an alarm when the patient get'
         b's disconnected (which technically, in our jargon, we would call a we'
         b'ak mitigation), it is to get the nurses to react, reconnect the pati'
         b'ent and keep him alive (what we would call a strong mitigation). To '
         b'achieve this latter goal, the system relies on the assumption that n'
         b'urses will react to the disconnection alarm. This assumption itself '
         b'has an obstacle \xe2\x80\x9cNurse Does Not React to Disconnection'
         b' Alarm\xe2\x80\x9d, which is even more likely to happen if the cr'
         b'itical disconnection alarm is similar to another non-critical alarm.'
         b' It is this obstacle that probably had not received sufficient atten'
         b'tion or wasn&#8217;t even considered during the system design and le'
         b'd to the incidents. The resolution that is being proposed now is'
         b' \xe2\x80\x9cGive the nurses better training\xe2\x80\x9d (an insta'
         b'nce of obstacle reduction in our framework). But an alternative reso'
         b'lution, that could have been chosen at design time, would of course '
         b'have been to make the &#8220;blue alarm&#8221; signalling an instrum'
         b'ent malfunction sound similar to the critical &#8220;red alarm&#8221'
         b'; rather than to the non-critical yellow one.</p>\n<p>The techniq'
         b'ues of goal-oriented obstacle analysis provides a modelling and anal'
         b'ysis framework to carry out this kind of reasoning in a systematic a'
         b'nd rigorous way. You can check <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staf'
         b'f/e.letier/publications/TSE-Obstacles.pdf">the paper </a>for details'
         b'.</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-content -->\n\t\t\n\t\t<footer cl'
         b'ass="entry-meta">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class="cat-links'
         b'">\n\t\t\t\t<span class="entry-utility-prep entry-utility-prep-ca'
         b't-links">Posted in</span> <a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/catego'
         b'ry/goal-modelling-2/" title="View all posts in Goal Modelling" rel="'
         b'category tag">Goal Modelling</a>, <a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.u'
         b'k/category/requirements-risks/" title="View all posts in Requirement'
         b's Risks" rel="category tag">Requirements Risks</a>\t\t\t</span>'
         b'\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t</footer><!-- #entry-meta --'
         b'>\n\t</article><!-- #post-668 -->\n\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t<articl'
         b'e id="post-310" class="post-310 post type-post status-publish format'
         b'-standard hentry category-collaborative-modelling-2 category-goal-mo'
         b'delling-2 category-research-impact category-system-evolution">\n\t'
         b'\t<header class="entry-header">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<h1 class="entry-title"'
         b'><a href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/goal-modelling-with-pelorus/" t'
         b'itle="Permalink to Goal Modelling with Pelorus" rel="bookmark">Goal '
         b'Modelling with Pelorus</a></h1>\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class="en'
         b'try-meta">\n\t\t\t\t<span class="sep">Posted on </span><a href="h'
         b'ttp://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/goal-modelling-with-pelorus/" title="8:59 '
         b'am" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2012-03-02T08:'
         b'59:36+00:00" pubdate>March 2, 2012</time></a><span class="by-author"'
         b'> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcard"><a class='
         b'"url fn n" href="http://letier.cs.ucl.ac.uk/author/ucaceyl/" title="'
         b'View all posts by Emmanuel" rel="author">Emmanuel</a></span></sp'
         b'an>\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-meta -->\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t</header><'
         b'!-- .entry-header -->\n\n\t\t\t\t<div class="entry-content">\n\t'
         b'\t\t<p>The first paper on <a title="seminal paper on goal modellin'
         b'g" href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/0167-6423%2893%2990021-G">goal-dr'
         b'iven requirements acquisition</a> was published in 1993. Since then,'
         b' it has been followed by a very large number of research papers, a c'
         b'omprehensive <a href="http://eu.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/produc'
         b'tCd-EHEP000863.html">book</a>, and a growing number of industrial ap'
         b'plications, but goal modelling is still something that is mostly don'
         b'e in universities and not so much elsewhere. In industry, current pr'
         b'actices are based on use cases, process modelling, and user stories;'
         b' you will rarely meet a requirements engineer or business analyst wh'
         b'o knows about goal modelling. This is despite a broad agreement that'
         b' existing requirements engineering practices don&#8217;t work so wel'
         b'l, precisely because they focus too much on the processes and the so'
         b'ftware (the how) and not enough on the goals (the why). So how can w'
         b'e fix this? How can we make goal modelling more broadly used? <a hre'
         b'f="http://easyweb.easynet.co.uk/iany/">Ian Alexander</a>, one of the'
         b' early adopters, says we\xe2\x80\x99ll know we\xe2\x80\x99ve been '
         b'successful when we\xe2\x80\x99ll regularly hear analysts saying t'
         b'hings like &#8220;<em>this use case relates to this goal</em><em> th'
         b'at contributes to this other goal and relies on this domain assumpti'
         b'on</em>.&#8221; To achieve this, we&#8217;ll need to simplify and co'
         b'mmunicate better the most essential ideas contained in our technical'
         b' research papers.</p>\n<p>With this in mind, I was captivated by '
         b'Vic Stenning&#8217;s talk &#8220;<a href="http://www.bcs.org/content'
         b'/conWebDoc/43612">Pelorus: a Tool for Business Change</a>&#8221; at '
         b'a meeting of the BCS Business Change Specialist Group last Thursday.'
         b' The talk consisted purely of discussions about goals, how to elabor'
         b'ate goal models by asking WHY and HOW questions, how to avoid confus'
         b'ing goals and activities, how to identify stakeholders by asking WHO'
         b' questions, how to define goals with measurable factors and targets,'
         b' and how to anchor risks analysis on specific goals instead of doing'
         b' it in a vacuum. Every concept had an almost direct relation to some'
         b' of our research papers: <a href="http://www.info.ucl.ac.be/~avl/avl'
         b'-fse08.pdf">goal-driven elaboration process</a>, <a href="http://www'
         b'.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/e.letier/publications/icse02.pdf">goal refinemen'
         b'ts</a>, <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/e.letier/publications'
         b'/letier-FSE04.pdf">measures of partial goal satisfaction</a>, <a hre'
         b'f="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/e.letier/publications/TSE-Obstacles'
         b'.pdf">obstacle analysis</a>. The only ideas I could see missing from'
         b' the discussions were <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/e.letie'
         b'r/publications/Conflicts-TSE.pdf">conflict analysis </a>and <a href='
         b'"http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/e.letier/publications/goalSim-RE2011.'
         b'pdf">reasoning about alternatives</a>.</p>\n<p>And Pelorus even b'
         b'rings something new and exciting to goal modelling. It is a lightwei'
         b'ght tool for <em>collaborative</em> modelling. The target domain for'
         b' Pelorus is the domain of business change initiatives. Studies show '
         b'that about 50% of all such initiatives fail. There are many reasons '
         b'for this, but one of the main factors is a failure to engage key sta'
         b'keholders early enough in the design of the changes. Vic quoted Rosa'
         b'beth Kanter: &#8220;<em>Change is disturbing when done to us, and ex'
         b'hilarating when done by us</em>&#8220;&#8212;a view I agree with ent'
         b'irely. The focus in Pelorus is on providing a platform that allows l'
         b'arge groups of stakeholders to collectively define and manage their '
         b'goals for a change project. Unlike other goal modelling tools such a'
         b's <a href="http://www.objectiver.com/index.php?id=4">Objectiver </a>'
         b'or <a href="http://jucmnav.softwareengineering.ca/ucm/bin/view/Proje'
         b'tSEG/WebHome">jUCM-Nav</a>, it is not meant to be used for a detaile'
         b'd goal-oriented elaboration of complete software requirements specif'
         b'ications.</p>\n<p>Pelorus is a web-based tool with a deliberate m'
         b'inimalistic design. The main concept is that of goal, a goal can sup'
         b'port other goals, goals must be well-defined and measurable, and&#82'
         b'12;apart from a few of other things such as the goal-based risk anal'
         b'ysis&#8212; that&#8217;s it. This is goal modelling stripped to its '
         b'bare minimum! Keeping it simple is essential to allow a diverse grou'
         b'p of stakeholders to contribute directly to its elaboration, but it '
         b'also ensures that everyone focuses on the goals and noting else. Thi'
         b's minimalistic design is reflected in a clean and simple user interf'
         b'ace that you can see in their <a href="http://www.toolforchange.com/'
         b'tour">videos</a>. Oh, maybe it&#8217;s a detail, but in Pelorus goal'
         b' models are not called models, they are <em><strong>maps</strong></e'
         b'm>. This is a term that was also used by another company <a href="ht'
         b'tp://www.kinetium.com/map/demo/demo_index.html">selling goal-oriente'
         b'd techniques</a>, so there might be something here.</p>\n<p><span'
         b" class='embed-youtube' style='text-align:center; display: block;'><i"
         b"frame class='youtube-player' type='text/html' width='584' height='35"
         b"9' src='http://www.youtube.com/embed/_rSmCfL7LYE?version=3&#038;rel="
         b'1&#038;fs=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&'
         b"#038;wmode=transparent' frameborder='0'></iframe></span></p>\n<p>"
         b'Once the goal map has been defined, Stakeholders continue to use Pel'
         b'orus to supervise the delivery and harvesting of the changes. This t'
         b'ransforms the goal model in a form of &#8220;living&#8221; business '
         b'case that, unlike traditional business cases that are written once a'
         b'nd then forgotten, can evolve throughout the change delivery. This i'
         b's another interesting idea that resonates with my current research i'
         b'nterests on system evolution.<strong></strong></p>\n<p>Pelorus co'
         b'uld be a good example of how research ideas transfer to practice, ex'
         b'cept that Vic Stenning had never heard about goal-oriented requireme'
         b'nts engineering. The main influence behind Pelorus, he says, is <a h'
         b'ref="http://wulrich.com/cst_brief.html">critical systems thinking </'
         b'a>&#8211;although, as far as I know, critical systems thinking doesn'
         b'&#8217;t include the kind of goal modelling approach present in Pelo'
         b'rus. Sure enough, the concepts of goals, goal decomposition, measura'
         b'ble objectives, and perhaps even obstacles are so common that one do'
         b'esn&#8217;t need to have read or heard about goal modelling to come '
         b'up with the same ideas. Yet, during the talk, the resemblances with '
         b'the research papers and <a href="http://www.info.ucl.ac.be/Research/'
         b'Publication/2001/RE01.pdf">tutorial </a>on goal-oriented requirement'
         b's engineering was striking. One person in the audience observed that'
         b' these ideas are very much in the air at the moment. As a researcher'
         b' who sometimes has to justify the public money spent on his research'
         b' by showing it has an impact, I like to believe that we have played '
         b'at least a small role in putting these ideas in the air. I hope Pelo'
         b'rus and other similar tools will continue to push these ideas forwar'
         b'd.</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t</div><!-- .entry-content -->\n\t\t\n\t\t<footer c'
